    id: 'Y8F01',
    title: 'The Last Ridge',
    type: 'fiction',
    source: 'Original',
    text: 'The storm arrived without warning. One moment the sky above the Kharven Ridge was a clean, pale blue; the next, a wall of grey cloud swallowed the peaks and the wind turned savage. Mara pressed herself against the rock face, her fingers finding a shallow crack, and told herself not to look down.\n\nShe had been climbing since dawn. The plan had been simple: reach the top, plant the school flag, photograph it for the geography project, and descend before lunch. Her partner, Dev, had twisted his ankle on the lower path and turned back two hours ago. She had carried on alone, certain the weather would hold. It had not. The sky had been so bright when she set off that she had left her spare fleece in the bag at the base station, a decision she was regretting deeply now.\n\nThe wind tore at her waterproof jacket as though trying to rip it from her body. Sleet needled her cheeks, turning her skin raw and pink. Each gust seemed to lean in close and whisper that she was small and foolish and very far from home. Mara ignored the whispers. She focused instead on the next handhold, the next ledge, the next six inches of upward progress. Focus was the only thing she had left to spend.\n\nHer water bottle was empty. Her energy bar had dissolved into soggy crumbs in her pocket sometime around midday. The cold had crept inside her gloves and begun to gnaw at her knuckles, patient as a rat. But above her, no more than thirty metres away, she could make out the angular silhouette of the summit cairn — a stack of flat stones left by previous climbers, each one a small act of defiance against the mountain.\n\nShe moved again. Right hand, left foot, breathe. The rock was wet and every surface wanted her gone. A loose stone skittered away beneath her boot and dropped into the white nothing below. She did not watch it fall.\n\nAt twenty metres from the top, the wind dropped suddenly. The silence was almost worse. In the stillness she could hear her own heartbeat, rapid and loud, and the faint moan of the cairn stones settling. She thought of her mother\'s face if she came home empty-handed. She thought of Dev waiting at the bottom with his bandaged ankle, not yet worried, just bored. She owed them both something. She wasn\'t sure what. She only knew that turning back now, so close, would feel like a different kind of failure — quieter than falling, but heavier.\n\nAt ten metres, the sleet returned. She climbed through it.\n\nWhen her palm slapped the flat top stone of the cairn, the sensation was so ordinary — cold, rough, solid — that she almost laughed. She pulled herself over the final lip, sat with her back against the cairn, and looked out at nothing: cloud in every direction, the world erased. She had reached the top of a mountain on a terrible day and there was nothing to see and no one to applaud. She pulled out her phone, took a photograph of the cairn, and began to make the plan for getting down.\n\nGetting down, she already knew, was the harder part.',
