        model: 'Model answer: The writer personifies the wind as a threatening voice that "lean[s] in close and whisper[s]" to Mara that she is "small and foolish," making the natural world seem actively malicious and personal rather than merely dangerous. The cold is compared to "a rat" gnawing "patient[ly]" at her knuckles — this unsettling simile implies a living, persistent threat that will not give up. Short, blunt sentences such as "She did not watch it fall" create tension by refusing to dwell on danger, mirroring Mara\'s own mental discipline and making the reader acutely aware of the drop she is ignoring.'
