        marks: 6,
        guidance: 'Indicative content: whole-text structural focus. Reward: opening in medias res with abrupt weather change creating immediate jeopardy; progressive countdown structure (30 metres, 20 metres, 10 metres) ratcheting tension; false release (wind drops at 20 metres) followed by renewed threat (sleet returns); shift in perspective inward — Mara\'s thoughts about family — adding emotional stakes; anti-climactic ending (no view, no applause) subverts expected heroic triumph, creating irony and a final twist of tension ("Getting down was the harder part"). Reward references to sentence length variation, the single-sentence paragraph "She climbed through it" as a structural beat. Top-level answers will discuss the overall arc and multiple structural choices with effect.',
        model: 'Model answer: The passage opens with a sudden, violent shift — "The storm arrived without warning" — placing the reader immediately in danger rather than building up to it slowly. The writer then uses a countdown structure (thirty metres, twenty metres, ten metres) to measure Mara\'s progress, each marker increasing the reader\'s anticipation. At twenty metres, the wind drops, offering a moment of false relief, before the sleet "returned" and the tension is restored. The single-sentence paragraph "She climbed through it" acts as a structural turning point — brief, determined, pushing past the pause. The ending deliberately withholds the expected reward: there is no view and no celebration. Instead, the final sentence — "Getting down, she already knew, was the harder part" — shifts the reader\'s anxiety forward rather than resolving it, ensuring the tension never fully lifts.'
