    id: 'Y8F02',
    title: 'The Cartwright Letter',
    type: 'fiction',
    source: 'Original',
    text: 'Nobody had been inside Flat 4B since the postman noticed the letters piling up. That was in February. By the time Jess and her mother moved into the building in late April, the police had come and gone, the flat had been declared empty, and a faint, lavender-and-old-paper smell had begun to seep under the door into the corridor.\n\nJess was twelve, curious, and easily bored. She told herself it was pure logic: if the previous tenant had left without collecting their post, something must have stopped them. And if something had stopped them, there might be a clue. She picked the lock — a skill she had learned from a library book and not yet told her mother about — and stepped inside.\n\nThe flat was tidy. That was the first strange thing. People who disappear in a hurry leave chaos: upturned drawers, half-eaten meals, a coat still on the hook. Here, every surface was clear. The kitchen smelled of bleach. The sitting room held a single armchair facing the window, a low table with a folded newspaper dated the fourteenth of February, and one white envelope propped against the lamp.\n\nThe envelope was addressed, in careful brown ink, to: The Next Person Who Reads This.\n\nJess stood very still. Her pulse was loud in the silence. She knew, with the particular certainty of someone who reads too many detective novels, that she should not touch the letter. She picked it up anyway.\n\nInside was a single sheet, covered in the same brown ink. The handwriting was small and precise, with elaborate curled capitals that made each line look like a musical score.\n\nI know you are wondering what happened to me, the letter began. So am I.\n\nJess read the rest of the page in one breath. The writer — who signed herself only as C. Cartwright — explained that she had been leaving notes around the building for three months. Each one contained a number. The numbers, placed in the correct order, would spell out the address of a safety-deposit box at a bank in the city centre. Inside the box was something she could not keep, something she had discovered by accident, something she needed a stranger to take to the right people. She did not say who the right people were. She did not explain what the thing was. She only said: I chose you. I chose the next person who was curious enough to come through that door.\n\nJess folded the letter. Her mouth was dry. Through the window she could see the grey courtyard below, empty in the afternoon drizzle. She thought about going to get her mother. She thought about calling the police. She thought about placing the letter back against the lamp and walking out of the flat and never coming back.\n\nShe did none of these things. She took a photograph of the letter with her phone, put it back exactly where she had found it, and went to look for the first number.',
