        model: 'Model answer: The writer structures the passage like an investigation, drawing the reader progressively deeper. It opens at a distance — we learn about the disappearance from the outside, through the postman\'s observation — before narrowing to Jess at the flat door, then inside, then to the single letter. This tightening of focus mirrors detective fiction and keeps the reader moving forward. The letter itself acts as the structural pivot: everything before it establishes mystery, the letter promises answers, and everything after shows those answers generating new questions. At the end, the writer uses a list of three sensible actions Jess considers ("She thought about going to get her mother... calling the police... walking out"), only to dismiss all of them in one flat sentence — "She did none of these things." This pattern-and-break structure reveals character economically and propels the story forward, leaving the reader where Jess is: committed to finding the first number.'
