        model: 'Model answer: The writer makes Jess immediately engaging through her voice — her decision to pick the lock is presented with wry humour as "a skill she had learned from a library book and not yet told her mother about," which makes the reader smile and want to be on her side despite the obvious rule-breaking. Her reasoning is also presented as intelligent rather than impulsive: she follows a logical chain — missing tenant, uncollected post, possible clue — rather than acting on simple boredom. However, I think the writer complicates a straightforward admiration. Jess herself knows she "should not touch the letter" and does so anyway; she considers contacting her mother or the police and deliberately chooses not to. These details make her interesting and realistic rather than simply admirable. The final action — photographing the letter and returning it precisely — shows shrewdness, and this perhaps is the quality the reader most admires: not courage or goodness, but a kind of cool-headed competence that promises she can handle whatever comes next.'
