    id: 'Y8F03',
    title: 'The Silk Road Messenger',
    type: 'fiction',
    source: 'Original',
    text: 'The caravanserai at Merv smelled of horses, woodsmoke, and the particular exhaustion of people who have been moving for a very long time. Yusuf had arrived three days ahead of the main caravan, riding alone and fast, and now he sat in the courtyard shadow watching the merchants and pilgrims argue over water prices and wonder if the eastern pass was blocked by snow. The air shimmered with heat even in the late afternoon, and the dust of a dozen different roads had settled on every surface, including, he supposed, himself.\n\nHe was fourteen years old and he was carrying a letter that could start a war.\n\nThe letter was sewn into the hem of his riding coat. He had not read it — his master, the merchant Altan, had made him swear on the names of his ancestors — but he had memorised every word of the instructions: deliver it only to the hand of Lady Soraya of the Blue Court, accept no deputy, speak to no one of your errand, and if you are taken, destroy it. The last instruction Altan had delivered with quiet eyes that made it clear he was not speaking only of the letter.\n\nYusuf drank his tea and watched the gateway.\n\nA man in a yellow coat had been watching him since the previous evening. Not constantly — he was careful, turning away at the right moment, finding other things to look at — but Yusuf had grown up in a city of traders and diplomats. He knew what being followed felt like. It felt exactly like this: the small pull at the back of the neck, the sense that the air around him was slightly too attentive.\n\nThe caravanserai was a good place to vanish. Two dozen caravans moved through it each week, carrying silk and spices east, carrying silver and glass west. Yusuf paid a boy three copper coins to create a distraction at the gate — a small argument about a mule, loudly conducted — and slipped out through the kitchen passage while the yellow-coated man turned to look.\n\nOutside, the city of Merv spread away in every direction: a maze of mudbrick walls, narrow lanes, workshops loud with hammering and the shouts of traders calling out their wares. Yusuf moved quickly, not running — running attracted attention — choosing turnings at random for the first ten minutes until he was confident the follower had not kept pace. Then he stopped, pressed himself into a doorway, and thought.\n\nLady Soraya\'s residence was two streets north. He had scouted it that morning: a high-walled compound with a blue tiled gate, guarded by two men who looked like they had been standing there since before Yusuf was born. He had no introduction. He had no gift. He had only a letter he could not describe and a name he was not supposed to say aloud.\n\nHe straightened his coat, feeling the slight weight of the hem. Then he walked towards the blue gate and knocked, clearly and without hesitation, as though he had been expected.',
