        guidance: 'Indicative content (reward any valid): identify methods AND their effect with quotation. Level 4 = perceptive, precise; Level 2 = identifies with some comment. Methods to reward: understated/euphemistic language creating sinister implication ("Altan had delivered with quiet eyes that made it clear he was not speaking only of the letter"); metaphorical sensory description of being watched ("the sense that the air around him was slightly too attentive"); juxtaposition of the ordinary (drinking tea) with high stakes (letter that could start a war); short declarative sentence for impact ("He was carrying a letter that could start a war"); the careful physical detail of the letter "sewn into the hem" implying the level of concealment required.',
        model: 'Model answer: The writer creates danger through understatement and implication rather than direct threat. Altan\'s warning about destruction is delivered with "quiet eyes" and the phrase "he was not speaking only of the letter" — the calm tone makes the threat more chilling than any violent language could, because the reader must complete the thought themselves. The sense of being watched is conveyed through an abstract metaphor: Yusuf feels "the air around him was slightly too attentive," which is an unusual and precisely unsettling image — it turns the environment itself into something hostile and alert. This is balanced against the ordinary detail of Yusuf drinking tea, so that the danger feels embedded in an everyday moment rather than dramatically signalled, which is arguably more threatening.'
