        model: 'Model answer: I strongly agree that the historical setting is vividly realised, and I think it does more than simply make the story exciting — it makes the story possible. The caravanserai is introduced through layered sensory detail — "horses, woodsmoke, and the particular exhaustion of people who have been moving for a very long time" — which gives the setting a texture that transports the reader without slowing the narrative. The city of Merv is sketched quickly but specifically: "mudbrick walls, narrow lanes, workshops loud with hammering" give it a physical reality that makes Yusuf\'s escape route credible. More importantly, the setting does narrative work: it is "a good place to vanish" precisely because "two dozen caravans moved through it each week," and the detail that Yusuf "had grown up in a city of traders and diplomats" explains his ability to recognise surveillance, connecting character directly to world. The excitement, I would argue, comes not just from the exotic setting but from how thoroughly the writer has thought through what that setting would mean for a young messenger — the copper coins, the kitchen passage, the blue-tiled gate all feel earned rather than decorative.'
