    id: 'Y8F04',
    title: 'Signal',
    type: 'fiction',
    source: 'Original',
    text: 'The message arrived on a Tuesday, which Priya always thought was the least dramatic day of the week to receive contact from an extraterrestrial intelligence.\n\nShe was running the overnight monitoring shift at the Farside Array, which meant she was alone in the relay station with two hundred radio telescopes, a flask of cold tea, and a novel she had already read three times. The array faced the permanent dark side of the Moon, shielded from Earth\'s electromagnetic noise, and its job was to listen. Usually it heard nothing. On most nights, Priya refilled her tea twice, read fifty pages, and filed a report confirming the universe had stayed silent. Tonight it heard something.\n\nThe signal was clean. That was the word that kept repeating in Priya\'s mind as she ran the verification checks: clean. Not the ragged static of a pulsar, not the rhythmic hiss of a gas giant, not any of the forty-three natural sources listed in the interference protocol she had memorised on her first week. This was structured. Eleven pulses, pause, then thirteen pulses, pause, then seventeen — each number prime, each gap precisely one second. Someone, somewhere, was counting.\n\nPriya\'s hands were steady as she initiated the logging sequence. She had trained for this. Everyone who worked at the Array had trained for this, in the same way that surgeons train for the rarest operations: methodically, seriously, never quite believing the day would come. She double-checked the calibration. She ran the interference sweep. She told herself to breathe.\n\nThe signal continued for forty minutes. Then it stopped.\n\nIn the silence that followed, Priya sat very still and thought about what she was about to do. Waking the Director meant waking the Deputy Director, which meant waking the UN liaison, which meant — within hours — the signal would belong to committees and press offices and governments. It would be documented, debated, leaked, and then officially confirmed or denied. The clean, simple fact of those seventeen prime numbers would disappear inside a machine of human complication.\n\nShe thought about this for eleven seconds. Then she picked up the emergency line.\n\n"Dr Okafor," she said when the Director answered. "I\'m sending you the log now. I think you need to see it tonight."\n\nShe listened to his silence on the line — the same quality of silence she had sat in herself, a moment earlier. A silence that had changed shape. Then he said, quietly: "Lock the building. Don\'t speak to anyone. I\'ll be there in forty minutes."\n\nPriya set down the phone. Through the observation window, the dark surface of the Moon stretched away in every direction, grey and still and ancient, scarred by a billion years of impacts it had absorbed without complaint. The Array\'s dishes were already moving, she realised — swinging slowly on their motors, reorienting themselves, all two hundred of them pointing in the same new direction. Listening again.\n\nShe hoped whatever was out there was also listening. She hoped, even more, that it was patient.',
