    text: 'Greyvane House had been empty for eleven years when the Alderton family moved in. The estate agent had called it a "project property," which was, as Nell\'s father pointed out, a polite way of saying that the roof leaked, the wiring was Victorian, and something had eaten most of the skirting boards in the east wing.\n\nNell was not afraid of old houses. She had grown up in a series of them, following her parents from one renovation to the next, and she had learned to see beauty in things that were tired. She liked the way Greyvane\'s ceilings were high enough to hold their own weather, the way the floorboards sang underfoot like an old instrument being played for the first time in years. She did not like the east corridor.\n\nThere was nothing wrong with it that she could name. The walls were papered in a faded pattern of grey birds in flight, the kind of birds you could only identify by their motion rather than their shape. The corridor ran the full length of the east wing, ending at a window that looked out onto the kitchen garden below. In the afternoon, the light through that window was long and golden and fell across the floor in a way that should have been welcoming. It did not feel welcoming.\n\nThe cold was the first thing. Not the damp cold of a room that had not been heated, but something more precise: a cold that existed in a stripe down the centre of the corridor, about the width of a person walking. Nell had measured it once with a thermometer she borrowed from the kitchen: four degrees lower than either wall. She told her father. He said the east wing probably had a different thermal mass from the rest of the house. He said this several times, in the slightly too-firm voice he used when he did not want to think further about something.\n\nThe second thing was the sound. Not every night, but often enough: a slow, deliberate knocking, like a single knock repeated at long intervals, originating from somewhere in the east wing\'s interior walls. The surveyor had suggested a loose pipe. The surveyor had not spent a night in Greyvane House.\n\nBut it was the birds that troubled Nell most. The grey birds on the wallpaper. She had mentioned, casually and once, to her mother that the birds seemed to have moved — that the cluster of five near the window had been together when she first arrived and now seemed to be spread further apart, with one or two clearly closer to the ceiling. Her mother had told her she was tired from the move.\n\nNell stood in the corridor on a Thursday evening in November, thermometer in hand, and studied the birds. Behind her, the house made its usual sounds: the tick of cooling radiators, the distant voices of her parents, the settling groan of old timber. Before her, the grey birds waited in their positions on the wall, each one caught mid-flight, each one facing, she now noticed, in exactly the same direction.\n\nTowards her.',
